<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-08-03T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-08-03T00:00:00-05:00" n="791" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d791">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/13614: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Hankow</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Josselyn</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Hankow</hi></placeName> [<date ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-outside-research" calendar="gregorian" when="1938-08-03">undated</date>].<lb/>[Received August 3—11:29 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Hankow raided by 18 Japanese bombers this morning. Bombs dropped in the
                            vicinity airfield.</p>
                        <p>Chinese customs vessel bombed and sunk by Japanese planes yesterday 36
                            miles below Hankow. Customs river officer J. T. C. Crawley, British, and
                            two members of Chinese crew were killed and several wounded. His
                            Majesty’s ship <hi rend="italic">Gnat</hi> proceeded scene early this
                            morning.</p>
                        <p>Repeated to Embassy and Peiping.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Josselyn</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>